---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Check Your Credit Score FREE | TrueCred Loan Expert">

<!-- Page Hero -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span>Credit Score</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Check Your Credit Score <span class="gradient-text">FREE</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Get your detailed credit report from all major bureaus instantly. Know where you stand and take control of your financial health.</p>
      <div class="hero-highlights">
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-bolt"></i>
          <span>Instant Report</span>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-indian-rupee-sign"></i>
          <span>100% Free</span>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-building-columns"></i>
          <span>All Bureaus</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page Content -->
  <section class="page-content">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="content-grid">

        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="content-main">

          <!-- Overview -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Overview</span>
              <h2>What is a Credit Score?</h2>
            </div>
            <p>A credit score is a three-digit number ranging from 300 to 900 that represents your creditworthiness. In India, the most commonly used credit score is the CIBIL score, maintained by TransUnion CIBIL. Other credit bureaus include Experian, Equifax, and CRIF High Mark.</p>
            <p>Your credit score is calculated based on your credit history, including repayment behaviour, credit utilization, length of credit history, credit mix, and recent credit inquiries. A higher score indicates better creditworthiness and increases your chances of loan and credit card approvals at favourable interest rates.</p>
            <p>Lenders use your credit score as a primary factor when evaluating loan applications. A score of 750 or above is generally considered excellent and gives you access to the best loan offers and lowest interest rates available in the market.</p>
          </div>

          <!-- Score Ranges Info Grid -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Score Ranges</span>
              <h2>Understanding Credit Score Ranges</h2>
            </div>
            <div class="info-grid">
              <div class="info-box">
                <div class="info-value" style="color: #22c55e;">750+</div>
                <div class="info-label">Excellent Score</div>
                <p>Best interest rates, instant approvals, highest loan amounts, premium credit cards with top rewards.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="info-box">
                <div class="info-value" style="color: #3b82f6;">700–749</div>
                <div class="info-label">Good Score</div>
                <p>Competitive interest rates, quick approvals, good loan amounts, access to most credit card offers.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="info-box">
                <div class="info-value" style="color: #f59e0b;">650–699</div>
                <div class="info-label">Average Score</div>
                <p>Higher interest rates, conditional approvals, limited loan amounts, fewer card options available.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Rate Table -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Score Impact</span>
              <h2>How Your Score Affects Loan Approval</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Your credit score directly impacts every aspect of your loan application — from approval chances to the interest rate you pay. Here's a detailed breakdown of how different score ranges affect your borrowing experience.</p>
            <table class="rate-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Score Range</th>
                  <th>Rating</th>
                  <th>Loan Approval</th>
                  <th>Interest Rate Impact</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>800 – 900</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #22c55e; font-weight: 600;">Exceptional</span></td>
                  <td>Almost Guaranteed</td>
                  <td>Lowest rates (9.5% – 11%)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>750 – 799</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #22c55e; font-weight: 600;">Excellent</span></td>
                  <td>Very High</td>
                  <td>Low rates (11% – 14%)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>700 – 749</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #3b82f6; font-weight: 600;">Good</span></td>
                  <td>High</td>
                  <td>Moderate rates (14% – 18%)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>650 – 699</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f59e0b; font-weight: 600;">Average</span></td>
                  <td>Moderate</td>
                  <td>Higher rates (18% – 24%)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>550 – 649</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f97316; font-weight: 600;">Below Average</span></td>
                  <td>Low</td>
                  <td>Very high rates (24% – 36%)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>300 – 549</strong></td>
                  <td><span style="color: #ef4444; font-weight: 600;">Poor</span></td>
                  <td>Very Unlikely</td>
                  <td>Usually rejected</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <!-- How Scores Work -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">How It Works</span>
              <h2>How is Your Credit Score Calculated?</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Credit bureaus use a proprietary algorithm that takes into account multiple factors from your credit history. Understanding these factors can help you take proactive steps to improve and maintain a healthy credit score.</p>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Payment History (35%)</strong>
                  <p>Your track record of paying EMIs, credit card bills, and other dues on time. Late payments, defaults, and settlements negatively impact this factor the most.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Credit Utilization (30%)</strong>
                  <p>The ratio of your current credit card balances to your total credit limit. Keeping utilization below 30% is recommended for a healthy score.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Credit History Length (15%)</strong>
                  <p>The age of your oldest and newest credit accounts, plus the average age of all accounts. A longer credit history generally results in a higher score.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Credit Mix (10%)</strong>
                  <p>Having a healthy mix of secured loans (home loan, car loan) and unsecured loans (personal loan, credit cards) shows lenders you can manage different types of credit responsibly.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>New Credit Inquiries (10%)</strong>
                  <p>Every time you apply for a loan or credit card, a hard inquiry is recorded. Too many inquiries in a short period can lower your score as it signals credit-hungry behaviour.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Tips to Improve -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Expert Tips</span>
              <h2>Tips to Improve Your Credit Score</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Improving your credit score is a gradual process that requires consistent effort and smart financial habits. Follow these expert-recommended strategies to boost your score over time.</p>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Pay All Bills on Time</strong>
                  <p>Set up auto-pay or reminders for all EMIs and credit card payments. Even a single missed payment can drop your score by 50–100 points. Consistency is the single most important factor.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Keep Credit Utilization Below 30%</strong>
                  <p>If your credit limit is ₹1 Lakh, try to keep your outstanding balance below ₹30,000. Request a credit limit increase if needed, but don't increase spending.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Avoid Multiple Loan Applications</strong>
                  <p>Each loan or credit card application triggers a hard inquiry. Space out applications by at least 3–6 months. Use pre-approved offers that involve only soft inquiries.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Maintain a Healthy Credit Mix</strong>
                  <p>A combination of secured and unsecured credit accounts demonstrates your ability to manage different types of debt responsibly. Avoid relying solely on credit cards.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Review Your Credit Report Regularly</strong>
                  <p>Check your credit report at least quarterly for errors or unauthorized accounts. Dispute any inaccuracies with the credit bureau immediately to prevent score damage.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Never Settle Loans — Always Close Them</strong>
                  <p>A settled account (paying less than owed) is viewed negatively by lenders. Always pay the full outstanding amount when closing a loan or credit card account.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Understanding Credit Report -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Credit Report</span>
              <h2>Understanding Your Credit Report</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Your credit report is a comprehensive document that contains detailed information about your credit history. It is prepared by credit bureaus based on data provided by banks and financial institutions. Understanding each section of your report helps you identify areas for improvement.</p>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Personal Information</strong>
                  <p>Contains your name, date of birth, PAN number, address, contact details, and employment information. Ensure all details are accurate and up to date.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Account Information</strong>
                  <p>Lists all your credit accounts including loans and credit cards, with details like account type, ownership, date opened, sanctioned amount, current balance, and payment history.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Inquiry Information</strong>
                  <p>Records all hard inquiries made by lenders when you apply for credit. Soft inquiries (self-checks) are also listed but don't affect your score.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Public Records</strong>
                  <p>Contains information about any legal proceedings, bankruptcies, or tax liens that may be associated with your credit profile.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Steps to Check Score -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Step by Step</span>
              <h2>How to Check Your Credit Score</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Checking your credit score with TrueCred is quick, easy, and completely free. Follow these simple steps to get your detailed credit report in minutes.</p>
            <div class="steps-grid">
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <h3>Enter Your Details</h3>
                <p>Fill in your full name, PAN card number, mobile number, and date of birth in the form. All fields are required for identity verification.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <h3>Verify via OTP</h3>
                <p>You'll receive a one-time password on your registered mobile number. Enter the OTP to securely verify your identity.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <h3>Get Your Score</h3>
                <p>Your credit score and detailed report from all major bureaus will be displayed instantly on screen. Download a PDF copy for your records.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <h3>Get Expert Advice</h3>
                <p>Based on your score, our experts will provide personalized tips and recommend the best loan and credit card offers available for your profile.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="content-sidebar">

          <!-- Check Score Form -->
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> Check Your Score</h3>
            <form class="sidebar-form" onsubmit="return false;">
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="Full Name" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="PAN Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="tel" class="form-input" placeholder="Mobile Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="date" class="form-input" placeholder="Date of Birth" required>
              </div>
              <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary btn-block" style="width:100%;justify-content:center;">
                Check Score <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
              </button>
              <p class="form-disclaimer">
                <i class="fas fa-lock"></i> 100% safe & secure. No impact on your score.
              </p>
            </form>
          </div>

          <!-- Quick Links -->
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-link"></i> Quick Links</h3>
            <ul class="sidebar-links">
              <li><a href="/pages/personal-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Personal Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/business-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Business Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/home-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Home Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/credit-cards"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Credit Cards</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/investments"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Investments</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/calculators"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> EMI Calculators</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/gold-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Gold Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/insurance"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Insurance Plans</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Credit Score</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>What is a good CIBIL score for getting a loan?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>A CIBIL score of 750 or above is generally considered good for getting a loan. With this score, you can expect quick approvals, lower interest rates, and higher loan amounts. Most banks and NBFCs prefer applicants with a score above 700, but having 750+ gives you access to the best offers and premium credit card options.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Does checking my credit score lower it?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>No, checking your own credit score is considered a "soft inquiry" and does not affect your score in any way. You can check your score as many times as you want without any negative impact. Only "hard inquiries" made by lenders when you apply for a loan or credit card can temporarily lower your score by a few points.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>How long does it take to improve my credit score?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Improving your credit score is a gradual process and typically takes 3 to 6 months of consistent effort. Simple steps like paying bills on time, reducing credit utilization, and not applying for new credit frequently can show results within a few months. However, recovering from major negative events like defaults or settlements may take 12–24 months or more.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Why is my credit score different across bureaus?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Each credit bureau (CIBIL, Experian, Equifax, CRIF High Mark) uses its own proprietary scoring model and may receive data from different lenders at different times. This can result in slight variations in your score across bureaus. The differences are usually minor (10–30 points), and all bureaus generally agree on whether your creditworthiness is good, average, or poor.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Can I get a loan with a low credit score?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>While it is more challenging, it is possible to get a loan with a low credit score. Some NBFCs and fintech lenders offer loans to applicants with scores below 650, though at higher interest rates. Options include secured loans (against property or gold), loans with a co-applicant who has a good score, or credit-builder products like secured credit cards that can help improve your score over time.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page CTA -->
  <section class="page-cta">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Ready to Check Your Credit Score?</h2>
      <p>Get your free credit report from all major bureaus in just 2 minutes. No hidden charges, no impact on your score.</p>
      <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">
        Check Score Now <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Footer -->

</BaseLayout>
